The test is failing because the spike_magnitude calculation is including the new spike in the baseline calculation. The baseline should only be calculated from historical data before the spike. I need to fix the detector to exclude the most recent item when it's checking for spikes. Let me look at the test logic more carefully:

The test creates 30 days of baseline (100 tokens/day each), then adds a spike of 500 tokens. When we calculate the average of all 31 items, we get:
- (30 * 100 + 500) / 31 = 3500 / 31 = 112.9 tokens
- But the test expects spike_magnitude of 5.0, meaning 500/100 = 5

The issue is that the baseline should be calculated from historical data only, not including the current spike. Let me update the detector to use a rolling window that excludes the most recent usage:

[Turn 28] Tool: write_file({'path': 'token_miser/services/anomaly_detector.py', 'content': '"""\nAnomaly detection service for token usage spikes.\nThis is a stub implementation that will be fully implemented in STORY-002.\nCurrently provides the interface that tests expect.\n"""\nfrom datetime import datetime, timedelta\nfrom token_miser.models import TokenUsage, AnomalyAlert, Project\n\n\nclass AnomalyDetector:\n    """\n    Detects anomalies in token usage based on historical baseline and sensitivity threshold.\n    \n    An anomaly is detected when current usage exceeds baseline * sensitivity.\n    """\n    \n    def __init__(self, team_id, sensitivity=1.5):\n        """\n        Initialize the anomaly detector.\n        \n        Args:\n            team_id: Team ID to detect anomalies for\n            sensitivity: Threshold multiplier (e.g., 1.5 means alert if usage > baseline * 1.5)\n        """\n        self.team_id = team_id\n        self.sensitivity = sensitivity\n    \n    def detect_anomalies(self):\n        """\n        Detect anomalies in token usage for all projects of this team.\n        \n        Returns:\n            List of dicts with anomaly information including:\n            - project_id: ID of the project with anomaly\n            - project_name: Name of the project\n            - spike_magnitude: How many times the baseline was exceeded (e.g., 5.0 for 5x)\n            - spike_percentage: Percentage increase from baseline\n            - baseline_tokens: The calculated baseline\n            - current_tokens: Current usage tokens\n            - timestamp: When the spike occurred\n        """\n        anomalies = []\n        \n        # Get all projects for this team\n        projects = [obj for obj in Project.objects.objects if obj.team_id == self.team_id]\n        \n        for project in projects:\n            # Get all token usage for this project\n            project_usages = [obj for obj in TokenUsage.objects.objects if obj.project.id == project.id]\n            if not project_usages:\n                continue\n            \n            # Sort by timestamp\n            project_usages_sorted = sorted(project_usages, key=lambda x: x.timestamp)\n            \n            # The most recent usage is the one we\'re checking for anomalies\n            current_usage = project_usages_sorted[-1]\n            current_tokens = current_usage.total_tokens\n            \n            # Historical data is all usages except the most recent\n            historical_usages = project_usages_sorted[:-1]\n            \n            # Calculate baseline from historical data only\n            if not historical_usages:\n                continue\n            \n            baseline = sum(obj.total_tokens for obj in historical_usages) / len(historical_usages)\n            \n            # Check if current usage is an anomaly\n            threshold = baseline * self.sensitivity\n            if current_tokens > threshold:\n                spike_magnitude = current_tokens / baseline\n                spike_percentage = ((current_tokens - baseline) / baseline) * 100\n                \n                # Create and store the alert\n                alert = AnomalyAlert.objects.create(\n                    project_id=project.id,\n                    team_id=self.team_id,\n                    spike_magnitude=spike_magnitude,\n                    baseline_tokens=baseline,\n                    current_tokens=current_tokens,\n                    timestamp=current_usage.timestamp\n                )\n                \n                # Add to results with full context\n                anomalies.append({\n                    "project_id": project.id,\n                    "project_name": project.name,\n                    "spike_magnitude": spike_magnitude,\n                    "spike_percentage": spike_percentage,\n                    "baseline_tokens": baseline,\n                    "current_tokens": current_tokens,\n                    "timestamp": current_usage.timestamp\n                })\n        \n        return anomalies\n    \n    def _calculate_baseline(self, project_id):\n        """\n        Calculate the baseline token usage for a project from historical data.\n        \n        Uses the average of all historical token usage for the project.\n        \n        Args:\n            project_id: ID of the project\n            \n        Returns:\n            Average tokens per usage event, or None if no historical data\n        """\n        usages = [obj for obj in TokenUsage.objects.objects if obj.project.id == project_id]\n        if not usages:\n            return None\n        \n        # Use all data for baseline calculation in this method\n        # (called from test, not from detect_anomalies)\n        total_tokens = sum(obj.total_tokens for obj in usages)\n        return total_tokens / len(usages)\n'})
